MIAmaxent — variable transformation and model selection for species distribution models

Julien Vollering

November 11, 2021

Background for the package

Maxent software (maxent.jar)

  1. variable transformation
  2. maximum entropy fitting
  3. lasso regularization

Take questions underway

.jar comes from Java, also available in R as ‘maxnet’ since 2017

More than 5,000 citations per mid-2019

variable transformation: like adding quadratic term to regression model

maximum entropy fitting: maximally uniform in space subject to constraints set by the presences

lasso regularization: model selection technique that emphasizes predictive power, not interpretability. Results in many variables in the model, and therefore complex model responses.

Many users keep default:

  • variable transformation types

  • regularization strength

leads to overfitted models

  • output format (logistic or cloglog)

easily misinterpreted

overfitting = lower prediction accuracy and overly complex models

default output formats are scaled to [0,1] so they look like probabilities but are not

MIAmaxent’s approach

  1. variable transformation based on expected occurrence-environment relationships
  2. choice of maximum entropy or logistic regression fitting
  3. model selection by forward stepwise selection

decoupled

forward stepwise selection rather than lasso regularization is really the biggest difference.

comparisons suggest that forward stepwise selection results in simpler models with equal or nearly equal predictive ability.

decoupling improves user control, allows fair methodological comparisons

Motivation

To improve on the success of the Maxent software by creating tools that produce more interpretable and ecologically-grounded models.

Especially suited to explain occurrence-environment relationships, and to make predictions outside the time and/or space of the training data.

A model selected by MIAmaxent (open) and one selected by maxnet (solid), both tuned to optimal complexity…

Not just a matter of maxnet defaults tending to overfit

Under lasso regularization, selection of predictors is secondary to parameter estimation, while under subset selection, parameter estimation is secondary to selection of predictors.

A word of caution on stepwise selection

  • p-values too low, CIs too narrow, etc, owing to multiple testing

  • struggles with collinear predictors

  • performs poorly when N:P ratio is low

  • undue emphasis on a single model

My recommendations with regard to MIAmaxent:

  • don’t treat p-values at face value

  • include known influences regardless of explanatory power (with formula)

  • use the threshold criterion alpha as a complexity penalty that needs tuning

MIAmaxent doesn’t help you with:

  • study area selection
  • data cleaning
  • sampling bias correction
  • (among other considerations)

Other distribution modeling packages:

dismo, biomod2, sdm, zoon, wallace, ENMTools, spThin, ENMeval, SDMtune…

readData()

makes it easy to read in data from CSV and ASCII raster files

Arguments:

occurrence, contEV, catEV — file pathways to the data

maxbkg — maximum number of background cells

PA — presence-absence or presence-only?

XY — include coordinates?

deriveVars()

creates derived variables from explanatory variables by a set of transformation types: linear, monotone, deviation, hinge, threshold, binary

Arguments:

data — data frame containing the response and explanatory variables

transformtype — which transformation types?

…

L, M, D, HF, HR, T (for continuous EVs), and B (for categorical EVs)

Spline type transformations (HF, HR, T) are pre-selected since there are limitless candidates

deriveVars()

der <- deriveVars(dat, transformtype = c("L", "M", "D", "T", "B"), quiet = TRUE)

selectDVforEV()

selects the parsimonious set of DVs which best explains occurrence, separately for each EV

Arguments:

dvdata — list of response variable followed by data frames of DVs

alpha — significance level used in nested model comparison tests (e.g. 0.01)

…

Forward stepwise selection

Nested model comparison tests (Chi-squared or F-test)

Alpha represents the selection criterion (more or less strict)

selectDVforEV()

selder <- selectDVforEV(der$dvdata, alpha = 0.01, quiet = TRUE)

selectEV()

selects the parsimonious set of EVs which best explains occurrence.

Each EV is represented by one or more derived variables.

Arguments:

dvdata — list of response variable followed by data frames of DVs

alpha — significance level used in nested model comparison tests (e.g. 0.01)

interaction — test interaction terms between pairs of EVs?

formula — include any EVs a priori?

…

selectEV()

selexp <- selectEV(selder$dvdata, alpha = 0.01, interaction=FALSE, quiet = TRUE)

plotResp()

plots the model response across a given EV in the model

Arguments:

model — model object

transformations — transformation functions used to create the DVs

EV — the name of the EV of interest

…

Single-effect response curves (plotResp) present the response of a model containing only the EV of interest. Marginal-effect response curves, where the other EVs are instead held at their mean values, are also possible (plotResp2). Results are usually qualitatively similar.

plotResp()

plotResp(selexp$selectedmodel, der$transformations, "easting")

projectModel()

calculates model predictions across any values of EVs.

Arguments:

model — model object

transformations — transformation functions used to create the DVs

data — values for all EVs in the model, as data frame or RasterStack

clamping — restrict values to the interval in the training data?

…

Spatial or non-spatial format, depending on how the EVs are supplied

projectModel()

ras <- stack("simdata/continuous/easting.asc", "simdata/continuous/northing.asc")
pred <- projectModel(selexp$selectedmodel, der$transformations, ras)

calculateFTVA(selexp)
##   variable  FTVA
## 1 northing 0.548
## 2  easting 0.452

Issue: misleading name. Actually calculates RVA (Halvorsen 2015).

Variable contributions calculated this way are path-dependent—small permutations could cause large differences in estimated contributions if these affect the order in which variables are selected.

What if we think that such an abrupt threshold response is implausible based on our knowledge of the ecology? Different options:

  1. Remove just northing_T12 from the dvdata and repeat DV and EV selection (not possible in maxent.jar)
  2. Disallow threshold transformations and repeat everything from variable transformation.

testAUC()

calculates AUC from provided test data

For an unbiased measure of model performance, best used with independently collected presence-absence data.

Arguments:

model — model object

transformations — transformation functions used to create the DVs

data — data frame containing the response and explanatory variables

…

AUC (and other common metrics) measures discrimination only! Calibration is often overlooked. 
PAdat <- readData(occurrence = "simdata/presence-absence.csv", 
                  contEV = "simdata/continuous/", 
                  catEV = "simdata/categorical/", 
                  PA = TRUE, XY = TRUE)
plot(pred$output)
points(PAdat$x, PAdat$y, pch=20, col=c("red", "blue")[PAdat$RV+1])

testAUC()

testAUC(selexp$selectedmodel, der$transformations, PAdat)

## [1] 0.6666667

Logistic regression

Logistic regression

Choose between maximum entropy model fitting and logistic regression (GLM) fitting with the algorithm argument.

Everything else is the same!

Maximum entropy fitting is generally used with presence-background occurrence data, while logistic regression is used with presence-absence data

Logistic regression

der <- deriveVars(dat, algorithm = "LR") #for pre-selecting spline transformations
selder <- selectDVforEV(der$dvdata, algorithm = "LR")
selexp <- selectEV(selder$dvdata, algorithm = "LR")

Getting started

Installation and finding help

install.packages("MIAmaxent") #currently v.1.2.0

To access documentation, use the ? command:

?MIAmaxent
?selectEV

Miscellaneous tips

  • EVs should be uniquely named, preferably without underscores (reserved for DVs) or colons (reserved for interaction terms)

  • Assign outputs of functions to objects — often you’ll need them later

    • Use .Last.value if you forgot and don’t want to rerun

  • The output of a function is frequently a list with named elements — use str()

readData() and deriveVars() replace spaces/underscores/colons with periods

Exercises

Model the relative probability of presence of semi-natural grasslands in Østfold County. This example data set is installed with the package and located here:

system.file("extdata", package = "MIAmaxent")

occurrence_PO.csv, occurrence_PA.csv, EV_continuous, EV_categorical

Use the MIAmaxent’s vignette for guidance or if you get stuck:

vignette("a-modeling-example", package='MIAmaxent')

also at

https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/MIAmaxent/vignettes/a-modeling-example.html

If you finish early, model absolute probability of presence with the presence-absence data.

Also feel free to use a different data set.
